Orchestrates a summarization run over an abstract `Fs` + `Agent`: writes leaf `.ctx` files for source files, then rolls those up into `rollup.ctx` files walked leaf-up (deepest directory first, repo root last). `intent.md` files are read as rollup input but never written by this file.

`load_prompts` reads `summarizer-leaf.md` and `summarizer-rollup.md` from `prompts_dir`, failing with `SummError::MissingPrompt` if either is unreadable — prompt text is never embedded in code. `summarize_leaf(fs, agent, prompts, src) -> Result<String, SummError>` validates `src` via `cpath::validate_rel`, checks `ctx_core::access::deny_reason` (using `fs.is_ignored`) to reject gated paths with `SummError::AccessDenied`, then reads the source, calls `agent.complete`, and writes to `cpath::leaf_ctx(src)`, returning the dest path.

`summarize_rollup` builds its prompt input via `assemble_rollup_input`, which concatenates the directory's `intent.md` (or `"(none)"`) with each child's summary: `.ctx` files are inlined directly, and subdirectories are represented by their `rollup.ctx` if one exists — `rollup.ctx` and `intent.md` themselves are skipped when iterating `cpath::context_dir_of(dir)`. Section labels and boundaries (`--- label ---`) are produced by `push_section`; changing this format changes what the rollup prompt sees for every child.

`run`/`run_with_prompts` are the two public entry points — `run` loads prompts from `prompts_dir`, `run_with_prompts` takes prompts already loaded (letting the prompt source and the summarized tree be different roots, e.g. prompts from cwd, target tree elsewhere). Rollup order comes from `affected_dirs`, which collects all ancestor directories of `targets` (via `cpath::ancestor_dirs`) into a `BTreeSet` then sorts by descending depth, ties broken alphabetically — so a directory's rollup is only generated after all its affected children's rollups, but siblings at equal depth complete in an unspecified sub-order relative to their own subtrees (safe only because depth strictly increases before it decreases).

`scope_check(count, approve)` guards against accidental large runs: errors with `SummError::ScopeTooLarge` if `count > MAX_TARGETS` (50) and `approve` is false. This is a pure count check — callers must invoke it themselves; `run`/`run_with_prompts` do not call it internally.